>no writing talent
Read this: http://www.jlakes.org/ch/web/The-elements-of-style.pdf
This is Elements of Style, a writing advice handbook originally published the same year World War fucking One ended.
I have mixed opinions on this book, but then again, every modern creative writer does. That's because of what the book argues is the highest level of writing a writer can manage: a police report. I'm being dramatic here and both Strunk and White would have my head for such audacity, but still.
Elements of Style will teach you how to write a dry retelling of events. It derides any sort of frivolous writing, over use of adjectives, and in general any kind of unnecessary prose regardless of how flavorful (I'm not advocating for purple prose by the way. That's just cancer.). This is because the original EoS was written at a time when the act of reading anything with more than three thousand words in it (that wasn't the Bible) was a high class past time and godDAMNIT we are going to be proper around here. It's been more modernized since then, but yeah. You get the picture.

Right, so you can tell, again, I'm of mixed feelings towards EoS. So why still recommend it? Because despite the fact that following it to the letter will result in writing drier than a baked rock, Elements of Style will teach you how to tell a story in the same manner a friendly Chad will help you with your deadlift form before you fuck up your back forever. He's just lookin' out for you, bro. Some of the rules are mandatory and are just grammatical law. Others are more akin to "You're probably going to fuck this up if you try, so lets save everyone the heartbreak and time by not doing it." Both types of rules are important.

In order to bend the rules of writing and flex some creativity onto the world, you have to know them. EoS is practically THE rulebook for story telling, because all it wants is for authors to tell the readers what happened. After that, you can get weird with it.
